%I A392499 #26 Mar 03 2026 04:07:23
%S A392499 20,45,70,88,104,105,165,175,189,195,255,272,285,304,350,368,385,441,
%T A392499 455,464,567,572,595,650,665,693,715,735,805,819,825,836,875,1001,
%U A392499 1015,1071,1085,1184,1225,1275,1287,1295,1309,1312,1323,1376,1435,1449,1463,1504
%N A392499 Numbers k > 1 with the smallest prime divisor p, where the sum of divisors d in the range 1 < d < k/p is at least k/p, but no subset of these divisors sums to k/p.
%C A392499 Equivalently, set D_{p}(k) = {1 < d < L : d | k}, where L = k/p. A term of this sequence is a noncomposable number (A392500) k such that Sum(D_{p}(k)) >= L, but no subset of D_{p}(k) sums to L.
%C A392499 We call these numbers 'rigid numbers' because, despite having enough admissible divisors 1 < d < k/p, their arithmetic structure prevents any subset from summing to k's largest proper divisor.
%C A392499 A392500 = this sequence U A392498; thus, noncomposable numbers are either sparse or rigid.
%C A392499 No term in this sequence is a prime number or a composable number (A392440).
%H A392499 Peter Luschny, <a href="https://github.com/PeterLuschny/Gists/blob/main/ComposableRigidSparse.ipynb">Composable, rigid, and sparse numbers</a>. A Python notebook.
%e A392499 The first few p-classes of rigid composites start:
%e A392499   p =  2 | 20, 70, 88, 104, 272, 304, ...
%e A392499   p =  3 | 45, 105, 165, 189, 195, 255, ...
%e A392499   p =  5 | 175, 385, 455, 595, 665, 715, ...
%e A392499   p =  7 | 1001, 1309, 1463, 1547, 1729, ...
%e A392499   p = 11 | 1573, 2431, 2717, 3289, 3553, ...
%o A392499 (Python)  # See also links.
%o A392499 # The function 'subset_sum_exists' is defined in A392652.
%o A392499 from sympy import divisors
%o A392499 def is_rigid(n: int) -> int:
%o A392499     if n < 4: return 0
%o A392499     divs = divisors(n)[1:-1]
%o A392499     if not divs: return 0
%o A392499     L = divs.pop()
%o A392499     if sum(divs) < L: return 0
%o A392499     return 0 if subset_sum_exists(divs, L) else divs[0]
%o A392499 print([n for n in range(1505) if is_rigid(n)])
%Y A392499 Cf. A392496 (p=2), A392495 (p=3), A392498 (sparse), A392500 (noncomposable), A392440 (composable), A392497 (minimal term), A006036 (primitive pseudoperfect).
%K A392499 nonn
%O A392499 1,1
